Zomato Restaurant Performance Analysis
Overview

This project analyzes Zomato restaurant marketplace data to identify the key drivers of revenue and order volume across restaurants.

The goal is to understand what differentiates high-performing restaurants from lower-performing ones and translate those insights into actionable business recommendations.

The analysis was conducted using Tableau and focuses on revenue concentration, pricing behavior, cuisine trends, customer engagement, and geographic patterns.

Tools Used
Tableau (data analysis & visualization)
Data Preparation
Joined datasets using: orders.r_id = restaurant.id
Aggregated order-level data into:
Total Revenue (sales_amount)
Total Orders (sales_qty)
Cleaned and standardized categorical fields:
Cuisine types
City/location fields
Grouped low-frequency categories into "Other" for clearer visualization
Analysis Questions

The analysis was structured around five core business questions:

Which restaurants generate the most revenue?
What differentiates high-performing restaurants from lower-performing ones?
Do restaurant costs impact order volume and revenue?
What is the relationship between cuisine type and performance?
What impact does location (city) have on performance?
Key Findings
Revenue Concentration

Revenue is heavily concentrated among a small number of restaurants.

Ratings vs Performance

Ratings show only a weak relationship with revenue.

Pricing & Cost Structure

Low-cost, high-volume models dominate overall performance.

Cuisine Performance

Cuisine type strongly impacts revenue distribution, with certain categories dominating overall market share.

Geographic Impact

Location-based insights were limited due to inconsistent dataset granularity.

Business Insights
Performance is driven primarily by volume, not pricing power
Ratings are secondary indicators
Cuisine selection is a major driver of revenue
Market performance is highly concentrated
Recommendations
Scale low-cost, high-volume models
Replicate strategies of top performers
Invest in high-performing cuisine categories
Use engagement metrics as secondary signals
Limitations
No marketing or promotion data
Limited competitive context
Geographic inconsistency
Revenue derived only from transaction data
Outcome

This project demonstrates structured analytical thinking using Tableau on imperfect real-world data.
